Cam Report

Lyron Winderbaum

9 August 2017

The Data

Here Ill go through a little dataset I collected in which the subjects are cams. Below is an image of a cam in use a size 6 Black Diamond Camalot C4, to be precise. A cam is a device mostly used in recreational rockclimbing that can be manipulated to have a variety of different widths and hence be placed into cracks of different sizes.

A #6 Black Diamond Camalot C4 placed in a crack (image taken from wikipedia).

There are several differernt brands that manufacture cams, and some of them provide useful charts such as the one below.

A cam comparison chart taken from the black diamond website).

Now this chart is great, but not all brands provide such a nice figure, and nobody provides a nice figure comparing different brands, or organising it differently to put similar sized cams next to each other, or looking at other factors like weight, etc. So I decided to go around to each of the brands websites and collect all the technical specifications and curate them into as single dataset, so that I could:

  • Figure out how to make weird plots like this, which show a range, using ggplot2 something I thought was pretty interesting.
  • Make other, more useful plots comparing different brands and placing cams of similar sizes next to each other so they can more easily be compared.

So I did that, collected technical specifcations for 196 cams from four different brands:

cam_df = read.csv('cam_df.csv', stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
head(cam_df)
##   Brand Variety NoCams Size Colour Weight Strength  Min  Max
## 1    BD      C3      3  000   grey     55        4  7.8 12.9
## 2    BD      C3      3   00 purple     57        6  9.0 13.7
## 3    BD      C3      3    0  green     59        7 10.7 15.8
## 4    BD      C3      3    1    red     62       10 12.0 18.8
## 5    BD      C3      3    2 yellow     66       10 14.2 22.6
## 6    BD      X4      4  0.1    red     51        5  8.4 13.8

Each row of this data.frame represents a different type or size of cam, and here I will give a more detailed description of each of the columns, or variables, recorded for each cam:

  • Brand The company that manufactured the cam. I collected technical specifications from four brands: BD (Black Diamond), Totemcam, Metolius, and DMM.
  • Variety a single brand often produces different varieties of cam, and this indicates this subdivision.
  • NoCams indicates the number of camming units in the cam, usually either three or four.
  • Size Usually a number, with the exception of the Metolius Super cams, used to identify different sizes within a single variety of cam, typically larger numbers indicate bigger cams.
  • Colour Often the different sizes are colour coded, although different brands can have different colour schemes.
  • Weight Weight in grams (g).
  • Strenth Rated strength in kilo-Newtons (kN).
  • Min Minimum width in centimeters (cm).
  • Max Maximum width in centimeters (cm).

Note that the values in the Colour column correspond to the colours as reported in the technical specifcations, which when given to ggplot2 as strings are interpreted as colours, but not neccessarily colours that actually look much like the colours of the cams themselves, so Ill make a few replacements to better match the look of the actual colours.

# Fluro green and lighter grey look bad
cam_df[cam_df$Colour == "green",        "Colour"] = "darkgreen"
cam_df[cam_df$Colour == "grey",         "Colour"] = "darkgrey"

# Metolius `light blue', `dark blue' and `light purple'
cam_df[cam_df$Colour == "light blue",   "Colour"] = "skyblue"
cam_df[cam_df$Colour == "light purple", "Colour"] = "orchid"
cam_df[cam_df$Colour == "dark blue",    "Colour"] = "darkblue"

# DMM `silver' (very dark grey)
cam_df[cam_df$Colour == "silver",       "Colour"] = "grey50"

For convenience Ill also create a unique identifier column by combining the Brand, Variety and Size columns.

cam_df$ID = paste(cam_df$Brand, cam_df$Variety, cam_df$Size)

Plots

# Compare C4s with corresponding sized Dragons
cam_subset = subset(cam_df, Variety %in% c('C4', 'Dragon'))
# Remove the two biggest C4 cams as they are bigger than the biggest Dragon Cams
cam_subset = subset(cam_subset, !((Variety == 'C4') & (Size %in% c('5', '6'))))
# Sort factor values neatly.
cam_subset = cam_subset[order(cam_subset$Brand, cam_subset$Min), ]

# using annotate()
n = nrow(cam_subset)
p <- ggplot()
p <- p + annotate("rect", xmin = (n - 0.5):0.5, xmax = (n + 0.5):1.5,
                  ymin = cam_subset$Min, ymax = cam_subset$Max,
                  alpha = 1, fill = cam_subset$Colour)
p <- p + annotate("text", x = n:1, y = (cam_subset$Min + cam_subset$Max) / 2,
                  label = cam_subset$ID, size = 2)
p <- p + scale_x_continuous(name = '', breaks = 1:n, 
                            labels = rev(cam_subset$ID))
p <- p + scale_y_continuous(name = "Range (mm)")
p <- p + theme(panel.grid.minor = element_blank())
p <- p + coord_flip()
print(p)

Nice. This is a comparison of DMM Dragon cams to BD Camalots, in the sizes in which they have comparable cams. But now that we have it in a data frame we can reorganise this to make a better plot:

# Sort factor values better.
tmp.order = ceiling((1:n)/2)
tmp.order[seq(2, n, 2)] = ((n / 2) + 1):n
cam_subset = cam_subset[tmp.order, ]

# using annotate()
n = nrow(cam_subset)
p <- ggplot()
p <- p + annotate("rect", xmin = (n - 0.5):0.5, xmax = (n + 0.5):1.5,
                  ymin = cam_subset$Min, ymax = cam_subset$Max,
                  alpha = 1, fill = cam_subset$Colour)
p <- p + annotate("text", x = n:1, y = (cam_subset$Min + cam_subset$Max) / 2,
                  label = cam_subset$ID, size = 2)
p <- p + scale_x_continuous(name = '', breaks = 1:n, 
                            labels = rev(cam_subset$ID))
p <- p + scale_y_continuous(name = "Range (mm)")
p <- p + theme(panel.grid.minor = element_blank())
p <- p + coord_flip()
print(p)

and we could plot weight on the y-axis, instead of ID:

# using annotate()
n = nrow(cam_subset)
p <- ggplot()
p <- p + annotate("rect", xmin = cam_subset$Weight - 4, 
                  xmax = cam_subset$Weight + 4,
                  ymin = cam_subset$Min, ymax = cam_subset$Max,
                  alpha = 0.4, fill = cam_subset$Colour)
p <- p + annotate("text", x = cam_subset$Weight, 
                  y = (cam_subset$Min + cam_subset$Max) / 2,
                  label = cam_subset$ID, size = 2)
p <- p + scale_x_continuous(name = 'Weight (g)')
p <- p + scale_y_continuous(name = "Range (mm)")
p <- p + coord_flip()
print(p)

we could zoom in a little and do a plot of all the cams in certain size range:

cam_subset = subset(cam_df, Max < 20)
# using annotate()
n = nrow(cam_subset)
p <- ggplot()
p <- p + annotate("rect", xmin = cam_subset$Weight - 0.8, 
                  xmax = cam_subset$Weight + 0.8,
                  ymin = cam_subset$Min, ymax = cam_subset$Max,
                  alpha = 0.4, fill = cam_subset$Colour)
p <- p + annotate("text", x = cam_subset$Weight, 
                  y = (cam_subset$Min + cam_subset$Max) / 2,
                  label = cam_subset$ID, size = 2)
p <- p + scale_x_continuous(name = 'Weight (g)')
p <- p + scale_y_continuous(name = "Range (mm)")
p <- p + coord_flip()
print(p)
